This lesson aims to teach you a little more about styling HTML
Specifically adjusting the padding of an element

There are three important properties which control the space that surrounds each HTML element
which are 'padding', 'margin' and 'border'

The intial code:
<style>
  .injected-text {
    margin-bottom: -25px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .box {
    border-style: solid;
    border-color: black;
    border-width: 5px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .yellow-box {
    background-color: yellow;
    padding: 10px;
  }

  .red-box {
    background-color: crimson;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 20px;
  }

  .blue-box {
    background-color: blue;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 10px;
  }
</style>
<h5 class="injected-text">margin</h5>

<div class="box yellow-box">
  <h5 class="box red-box">padding</h5>
  <h5 class="box blue-box">padding</h5>
</div>

The task required me to change the 'padding' of the blue box to match the padding of the red box.

This was my code (specifcally around the padding for red and blue box):
 .red-box {
    background-color: crimson;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 20px;
  }

  .blue-box {
    background-color: blue;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 20px;
  }
  
See how the padding was initially at 10px(pixels) for the blue box and 20px for the red box.
All I had to do to match the padding was to increase the blue box padding by 10px resulting in 20px.
Therefore resulting in the blue box and red box being the same in terms of padding.
You can see this effect being reflected in the test environment.
